It would be easiest to use a Fortran compiler that is compatible with 
Visual Studio .NET.  I think the Intel Fortran compiler is.  Since I 
hardly ever use a PC anymore, perhaps someone else can better answer 
this question.

The f77 and f90 demo programs can all be built very easily on systems 
that support the GNU tools (make, autoconf, etc.) and compilers (g++, 
g77).  In my opinion, anyone planning to do serious work in Fortran (or 
C++) with Cantera should at least consider getting a machine that runs 
some unix-like operating system, such as linux or Mac OS X.  You can 
get one for less than $1K, and don&#39;t need to buy expensive commercial 
compilers.  Just a thought...

Dave G.


